	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>ACP should harmonise EPA sensitive lists to promote regional trade </h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Research published by the United Nations University Institute on Comparative Regional Integration Studies (UNU-CRIS) warns that (I)EPA reciprocity ‘will tend to threaten intra-regional trade in ACP groupings’ both through ‘a direct displacement threat to existing regional suppliers’ by tariff-free European exports and through ‘the displacement of domestic production by European exporters in domestic markets’, reducing regional production capacity. It argues that these threats can be offset in a number of ways, most obviously by harmonising each signatory’s list of sensitive products (on which liberalisation is excluded or postponed) so that they focus on regionally traded goods. In addition, the EU could support measures that enhance the productivity and competitiveness of domestic producers, and export capacity (both intra- and extra-regional).</p><p>The paper notes that ‘although promoting regional integration was an objective of EPAs, relatively limited attention has been given to how the structure of final agreements could support and facilitate regional integration.’ While all of the EPAs already contain the parties’ liberalisation schedules, there will be opportunities to agree revisions, both during the negotiation of full agreements in those regions that have only signed (or initialled) interim accords and through the regular consultative mechanisms provided in each treaty.</p><p>The report builds on the foundations established by a number of <i>ex ante</i>&nbsp;partial equilibrium modelling studies of the trade effects of EPAs on various ACP groupings or countries. These measured the regional trade displacement effects of the liberalisation of tariffs on imports from the EU, with special attention given to agriculture in some of the studies. The report goes beyond this to consider the associated adjustment effects on the regional exporting countries, and how tariff reforms and other measures can be designed to reduce adverse regional trade development effects.</p><p>The study finds that while the welfare effects of the (I)EPAs studied are small relative to GDP, and are positive overall and on average, between a third and over a half of countries (depending on the assumptions) experience a small negative welfare effect. More seriously, ‘the revenue losses and trade effects (increase in imports) are more significant, and as the costs of increased import competition are concentrated in particular sectors, small welfare effects do not imply small adjustment costs.’ In the specific case of Mauritius, for example, the authors find that ‘the adjustment effects are likely to be considerable’ and conclude that the same may be true for some other ACP countries.</p><p>This is salutary information, given that there are signs that both the SADC and EAC IEPAs may be signed in 2011, with South African Trade Minister Rob Davies, for example, predicting mid year for the former, and signs also that the proposed fusion of the EAC, COMESA and SADC regional integration schemes is set to move forward strongly. Even without the EPAs, the East Africa Legislative Assembly (EALA) has expressed concern over the slow progress of liberalisation within EAC, and has urged that completing this task should take precedence over the EPA. Following a session of the assembly in late 2010, the regional press reported that the EALA members ‘contend that the EAC Common Market would thrive in a regime of harmonised policies, laws and systems but noted [that] the pace of the harmonisation processes in areas such as education, internal taxes and cross border systems, among others, is inadequate.’</p>
		
		
