				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The desirability of nurturing regional trade is a widely held view in the ACP – and was a stated objective of the EPAs. Achieving this goal would be greatly facilitated if members of EPAs liberalised the same goods over the same timetable as each others. But the reality is that most national liberalisation and exclusion schedules have very limited overlap with those of partner EPA members. Only the EAC IEPA and the SACU schedules within the SADC IEPA have the same timetable and exclusions, while the CARIFORUM EPA has widely differing timetables but an (almost) common exclusion list by the end of the implementation period. The signatories to the ESA IEPA have not even always used the same product definitions in their schedules. And, of course, there is a complete mismatch between the import policy of (I)EPA members and non-members within the same regional group.</p><p>As the UNU report makes clear, there is time to revise these schedules during the extended implementation periods negotiated in most, but not all, (I)EPAs. The issues involved are serious ones; the differences in national exclusion schedules reflect perceived differences in national interests. But every opportunity needs to be taken to whittle away at a new threat to established and future intra-regional trade. While support to make regional export producers more competitive is the ‘ideal’ solution (since it will also benefit extra-regional exports and consumers in the importing states), moves to avoid a premature opening to unrestricted competition from European suppliers are also desirable. To ensure balance between the more and less industrialised ACP states, this should give strong attention to regional trade in agricultural goods.</p>
		</div>
		
